The old familiar faces of the new anti-Semitism.
Why do so many survivors of the Holocaust sense emerging threats to Judaism, even before they become generally visible?
Because they know that the supposedly harmless hints can escalate to accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that can be legally entrenched.
At that point, hysteria then sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm, because they know what's at stake in the game.
With this, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we may also survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential election, we have all reason to listen.
But not just demagogues like Jean-Marie Le Pen or other rough right-wing extremists in Europe cause difficulties.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became opportunists of fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" in conjunction with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language often reminiscent of that of the opportunists of these antidemocratic movements.
It's not about the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, thank goodness - but it's the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the UK should be mentioned: Recently, he titled Israel as "this damn little country" during a dinner party in London.
His coarse manner of speaking is not particularly frightening.
What is more alarming are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government demand his recall. The matter was ticked off as another scandal in public.
The French press portrayed the ambassador seriously as a victim of British small fry leaks, not of his own despicable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has numerous allies among Europe's elite.
Ambassador Bernard did us a service, however: through him it became clear how widespread these new anti-Semitic sentiments are.
As a columnist so aptly put it: Israel has become a hate object, whose naming one dares not to utter.
But we are not only required to take the risk, we are even obligated to express it.
In light of the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we cannot remain silent.
It's a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We cannot remain silent about the denial of the Holocaust, which is becoming increasingly commonplace. No less can we remain silent about the comparisons that anti-Semites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers in a Palestinian television show, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "stand up to the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It's not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. Almost everyone hates them."
During a televised Friday prayer broadcast on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. Wherever you are, kill them and these Americans, who are just like them."
What we should think in connection with anti-Semitism is that it always starts with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Semitism is not checked, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore a task for both Jews and non-Jews.
The attack points in this fight are less clear than ever before, as one astonishing aspect of today's anti-Semitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of anti-Semitism remains the same - namely to attack Jews - it nonetheless changes its face, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
The Jewish religion was once the goal.
When she did not give in, the Jews were driven out or killed.
As in the 19th century, the theory of race drew people under its spell, the Jews were attacked because of their belonging to an evil race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today being discredited as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
Just as with other nations, it is perfectly legitimate to be critical of certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Anti-Zionism is increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of Great Britain, but I'm not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
No one would believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
However, there are people in connection with Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
Israel-bashing is on the agenda in various UN organisations.
The demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Middle East is a key point of this new antisemitism.
If Israel is described as the "enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil", then within the UN, the "teaching of contempt" is being spread, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, Member of Parliament for Canada.
This permanent presentation of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in truth a campaign against the Jewish people.
These numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are rooted in the demonizations of Israel, which employ antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in conjunction with the Middle East.
In comparison to previous anti-Semitic outbreaks, the current anti-Semitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, and more about an attack on the "collective Jew", namely the state of Israel.
Such attacks have, however, set off a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world Jew-free.
The most dangerous anti-Semites today are those who want to make the world judenrein.
